{
  "What is dimensional analysis?": "",
  "A technique using dimensions to check equations and convert units": "",
  "A way to draw 3D graphs": "",
  "A type of laboratory experiment": "",
  "A method for calculating mass": "",
  "Dimensional analysis is a technique that uses the dimensions (units) of physical quantities to check equations, convert units, and derive relationships between variables.": "",
  "What must be true for a physics equation to be valid dimensionally?": "",
  "Both sides must have the same numbers": "",
  "The left side must be larger": "",
  "Both sides must have the same dimensions": "",
  "Units don't matter in equations": "",
  "For a physics equation to be dimensionally valid, every term on the left side must have the same dimensions as every term on the right side. If dimensions do not match, the equation is incorrect.": "",
  "What are the dimensions of velocity?": "",
  "[L][T]^-1": "",
  "[L]^2[T]^-1": "",
  "[M][T]^-1": "",
  "[M][L][T]^-2": "",
  "Velocity = distance / time, so its dimensions are [L][T]^-1 (length divided by time). This is one of the most fundamental dimensional relationships.": "",
  "What are the dimensions of force?": "",
  "[L][T]^-2": "",
  "[M][L]^2[T]^-2": "",
  "[M][L][T]^-1": "",
  "Force = mass x acceleration, so its dimensions are [M][L][T]^-2. This follows from F = ma where mass has dimensions [M] and acceleration has dimensions [L][T]^-2.": "",
  "Can dimensional analysis determine dimensionless constants?": "",
  "Yes, always": "",
  "Only sometimes": "",
  "No, never": "",
  "Yes, partially": "",
  "Dimensional analysis cannot determine dimensionless constants (like 2, pi, or 1/2) because these numbers have no units. It can only work with quantities that carry dimensions.": "",
  "What is a conversion factor?": "",
  "A constant that appears in every equation": "",
  "The ratio of two different physical quantities": "",
  "A number that changes the laws of physics": "",
  "A fraction equal to 1 used to convert between units": "",
  "A conversion factor is a ratio equal to 1 that lets you change from one unit to another without changing the value. For example, (1000 m / 1 km) = 1.": "",
  "What are the dimensions of energy?": "",
  "[M][L]^2[T]^-1": "",
  "Energy = force x distance, so its dimensions are [M][L][T]^-2 x [L] = [M][L]^2[T]^-2. This applies to all forms of energy (kinetic, potential, thermal, etc.).": "",
  "What are the dimensions of acceleration?": "",
  "[L]^2[T]^-2": "",
  "Acceleration = velocity / time = [L][T]^-1 / [T] = [L][T]^-2. Its SI unit is m/s^2, which confirms the dimensions of length divided by time squared.": "",
  "What are the three fundamental dimensions used in mechanics?": "",
  "Force, energy, and power": "",
  "Speed, velocity, and acceleration": "",
  "Mass, length, and time": "",
  "Newton, joule, and watt": "",
  "In mechanics, the three fundamental dimensions are mass [M], length [L], and time [T]. All mechanical quantities can be expressed using combinations of these three dimensions.": "",
  "What are the dimensions of pressure?": "",
  "[M][L]^-1[T]^-2": "",
  "[M][L]^-2[T]^-1": "",
  "Pressure = force / area = [M][L][T]^-2 / [L]^2 = [M][L]^-1[T]^-2. Its SI unit is the Pascal (Pa = N/m^2 = kg/(m*s^2)).": "",
  "What does the term 'dimension' mean in physics?": "",
  "The physical nature of a quantity expressed in terms of base quantities like mass, length, and time": "",
  "The total number of spatial directions in which an object is able to move freely": "",
  "The numerical value obtained when a physical quantity is measured with an instrument": "",
  "The size of an object measured along its longest side from end to end": "",
  "In physics, a dimension refers to the physical nature of a quantity in terms of fundamental quantities. For example, velocity has the dimension of length per time, regardless of whether it is measured in m/s or km/h.": "",
  "What does 'dimensionally homogeneous' mean for an equation?": "",
  "Every term in the equation has the same dimensions on both sides": "",
  "All variables in the equation are measured in the same SI units": "",
  "The equation contains exactly the same number of terms on each side": "",
  "All the numbers in the equation are positive integers without decimals": "",
  "A dimensionally homogeneous equation has matching dimensions on both sides and in every term that is added or subtracted. This is a necessary (but not sufficient) condition for an equation to be correct.": "",
  "What does the symbol [M] represent in dimensional analysis?": "",
  "The dimension of mass": "",
  "The dimension of momentum": "",
  "The prefix mega in SI units": "",
  "The dimension of meters": "",
  "[M] represents the dimension of mass in dimensional analysis. It is one of the three fundamental dimensions in mechanics, along with [L] for length and [T] for time.": "",
  "What is a 'dimensionless quantity'?": "",
  "A quantity that has no physical meaning in any context whatsoever": "",
  "A pure number with no units, such as a ratio or counting number": "",
  "A quantity that can only be measured using the imperial system of units": "",
  "A quantity that has dimensions too small to be detected by instruments": "",
  "A dimensionless quantity is a pure number with no units. Examples include pi, angles in radians, and ratios like the coefficient of friction. Dimensional analysis cannot determine these values.": "",
  "What is the meaning of 'dimensional consistency'?": "",
  "The requirement that both sides of an equation have identical dimensions": "",
  "The requirement that all measurements use identical measuring instruments": "",
  "The requirement that all quantities in a problem have the same magnitude": "",
  "The requirement that all calculations are done using the same calculator": "",
  "Dimensional consistency means that both sides of an equation must have the same dimensions. If they do not match, the equation is definitely wrong, regardless of the numerical values.": "",
  "What does the symbol [T] represent in dimensional analysis?": "",
  "The dimension of temperature": "",
  "The dimension of time": "",
  "The prefix tera in SI units": "",
  "The dimension of torque": "",
  "[T] represents the dimension of time in dimensional analysis. Its SI unit is the second (s). Temperature uses the symbol [Theta] or [K] to avoid confusion.": "",
  "What does 'deriving a formula' mean using dimensional analysis?": "",
  "Finding the relationship between quantities by matching their dimensions": "",
  "Copying a formula directly from a textbook without any changes at all": "",
  "Measuring all quantities in a lab and creating a data table of results": "",
  "Using a calculator to evaluate a formula with specific numerical inputs": "",
  "In dimensional analysis, deriving a formula means figuring out how quantities must combine (multiply, divide, etc.) so that the dimensions balance. This reveals the functional relationship, though not dimensionless constants.": "",
  "What does 'unit conversion' mean in the context of dimensional analysis?": "",
  "Changing the numerical value and unit of a quantity while keeping the actual amount the same": "",
  "Changing the physical quantity being measured from one type to a completely different type": "",
  "Rounding a measurement to a smaller number of significant figures for convenience": "",
  "Replacing all units in a formula with dimension symbols like M, L, and T": "",
  "Unit conversion changes the unit of a measurement without changing the actual quantity. For example, 1 km = 1000 m; the distance is the same, just expressed differently.": "",
  "What does the symbol [L] represent in dimensional analysis?": "",
  "The dimension of luminosity": "",
  "The dimension of length": "",
  "The SI unit liter": "",
  "The dimension of load": "",
  "[L] represents the dimension of length in dimensional analysis. Its SI unit is the meter (m). All distances, heights, widths, and displacements have the dimension [L].": "",
  "What are the dimensions of power?": "",
  "[M][L]^2[T]^-3": "",
  "[M][L][T]^-3": "",
  "Power = energy / time = [M][L]^2[T]^-2 / [T] = [M][L]^2[T]^-3. Its SI unit is the watt (W = J/s = kg*m^2/s^3).": "",
  "A student writes the equation v = at^2 for velocity. Using dimensional analysis, is this equation dimensionally correct?": "",
  "Yes, because acceleration times time squared gives velocity": "",
  "No, because [L][T]^-2 times [T]^2 gives [L], not [L][T]^-1": "",
  "Yes, because all kinematic equations are dimensionally correct": "",
  "No, because acceleration must be divided by time, not multiplied": "",
  "Checking: v has dimensions [L][T]^-1. at^2 has dimensions [L][T]^-2 * [T]^2 = [L]. Since [L][T]^-1 does not equal [L], the equation is dimensionally incorrect. The correct equation is v = at.": "",
  "A student needs to convert 72 km/h to m/s for a lab calculation. What is the correct result?": "",
  "7.2 m/s": "",
  "20 m/s": "",
  "2 m/s": "",
  "200 m/s": "",
  "72 km/h x (1000 m / 1 km) x (1 h / 3600 s) = 72000/3600 = 20 m/s. The conversion factors cancel km and h, leaving m/s.": "",
  "A student claims that the formula for kinetic energy is E = mv (mass times velocity). Can dimensional analysis disprove this?": "",
  "No, because mv has the correct dimensions of energy [M][L]^2[T]^-2": "",
  "Yes, because mv has dimensions [M][L][T]^-1, not [M][L]^2[T]^-2": "",
  "No, dimensional analysis cannot check any formulas involving energy": "",
  "Yes, because mass and velocity cannot be multiplied in any formula": "",
  "Energy has dimensions [M][L]^2[T]^-2, but mv has dimensions [M] * [L][T]^-1 = [M][L][T]^-1. These do not match, so E = mv is dimensionally wrong. The correct formula is E = (1/2)mv^2.": "",
  "In a lab report, a student writes F = mv^2/r for centripetal force. Is this dimensionally consistent with force?": "",
  "No, it has dimensions of energy, not force": "",
  "Yes, mv^2/r has dimensions [M][L][T]^-2, which matches force": "",
  "No, dividing by r makes the dimensions incorrect for any force": "",
  "Yes, but only when the object moves in a perfectly circular path": "",
  "Check: [M][L]^2[T]^-2 / [L] = [M][L][T]^-2. This matches the dimensions of force [M][L][T]^-2, so the equation is dimensionally correct.": "",
  "A physics teacher asks students to check whether the equation x = v^2 / (2a) is dimensionally correct for displacement. What do they find?": "",
  "It is incorrect because dividing by acceleration always gives time": "",
  "It is correct because [L]^2[T]^-2 / [L][T]^-2 = [L], matching displacement": "",
  "It is incorrect because the left side has dimension [L] but the right side has [T]": "",
  "It is correct because all kinematic equations are automatically dimensionally valid": "",
  "v^2 has dimensions [L]^2[T]^-2 and a has dimensions [L][T]^-2. So v^2/a = [L]^2[T]^-2 / [L][T]^-2 = [L]. This matches displacement, so the equation is dimensionally correct.": "",
  "A student converts 9.8 m/s^2 to km/h^2 for a project. Which conversion factors should they use?": "",
  "(1 km / 1000 m) and (3600 s / 1 h)^2": "",
  "(1000 m / 1 km) and (1 h / 3600 s)^2": "",
  "(1 km / 1000 m) and (1 h / 3600 s)": "",
  "(1000 m / 1 km) and (3600 s / 1 h)": "",
  "To convert m to km, use (1 km / 1000 m). To convert s^2 to h^2, use (3600 s / 1 h)^2, because the time unit is squared in acceleration. This gives 9.8 x (1/1000) x (3600)^2 = 127,008 km/h^2.": "",
  "A student proposes that the period of a pendulum depends on mass (m), length (L), and gravity (g). Dimensional analysis shows the period depends on which combination?": "",
  "sqrt(m / g) because mass and gravity are the key factors": "",
  "sqrt(L / g) because only length and gravity give the dimension of time": "",
  "m * L / g because all three variables must appear in the formula": "",
  "L * g because multiplying length and gravity gives the dimension of time": "",
  "Period has dimension [T]. L/g has dimensions [L] / [L][T]^-2 = [T]^2, so sqrt(L/g) has dimension [T]. Mass does not appear because no combination of [M] with [L] and [T]^-2 produces [T] alone.": "",
  "A student writes the equation for gravitational potential energy as E = mgh^2. Using dimensional analysis, is this correct?": "",
  "Yes, because mass times gravity times height squared gives energy": "",
  "No, because mgh^2 has dimensions [M][L]^3[T]^-2, not [M][L]^2[T]^-2": "",
  "Yes, because squaring height accounts for the 1/2 factor in energy": "",
  "No, because gravity g cannot be multiplied by height h in any formula": "",
  "Energy has dimensions [M][L]^2[T]^-2. mgh^2 = [M] * [L][T]^-2 * [L]^2 = [M][L]^3[T]^-2. The dimensions do not match, so the equation is wrong. The correct formula is E = mgh.": "",
  "A lab group needs to convert a density of 2.7 g/cm^3 to kg/m^3. What is the result?": "",
  "2700 kg/m^3": "",
  "0.0027 kg/m^3": "",
  "270 kg/m^3": "",
  "27000 kg/m^3": "",
  "2.7 g/cm^3 x (1 kg / 1000 g) x (100 cm / 1 m)^3 = 2.7 x (1/1000) x (1,000,000) = 2700 kg/m^3. The cm^3 to m^3 conversion requires cubing the linear factor.": "",
  "A student checks the equation for wave speed: v = f * lambda (frequency times wavelength). Is this dimensionally correct for velocity?": "",
  "No, because frequency times wavelength gives dimensions of acceleration": "",
  "Yes, because [T]^-1 * [L] = [L][T]^-1, which matches velocity": "",
  "No, because frequency has no dimensions and wavelength has dimension [L]": "",
  "Yes, because any product of two physics quantities gives velocity dimensions": "",
  "Frequency has dimensions [T]^-1 and wavelength has dimensions [L]. Their product is [T]^-1 * [L] = [L][T]^-1, which matches velocity. The equation is dimensionally correct.": ""
